|      10.1109/ACCESS.2020.3007338      | 2020 |           Cloud           | 4-6 | No  | S, T, R, I, D, E |        Attack graphs        |       T1, T2       |       Empirical       |                       human-error, challenges in securing cloud systems                        |                            CE techniques for testing cloud systems                             |                                               Cloudstrike is used to proactvively indentify security vulnerabilities in cloud platfrom and infrastructures.                                                |                                                        All components of CloudStrike are implemented in Java,_x000D_ attacks are transmitted to the cloud platforms using APIs of_x000D_ AWS and GCP, hence there is no need to install agents on target cloud infrastructure.                                                         | Cloudstrike uses uses chaos algorithms to inject security faults into cloud infrastructure. To do so, first it builds a hypothesis around a steady state behaviour. Second, it esecutes random actions against the targeted cloud system and run experimetns automatically in production while controlling the risk of system failure by reducing the blast radius. The experimetns are monitored and analysed to collect observations and detect vulnerabilities. The acuired knowledge is then used to hardening the security measure and in preparing the subsequent fault injection campaigns. All the observations, falut models, security best practices, and sure baselines are stored in a knowledge base. | Attack graphs: GraphViz (SW), Dot (SW), Terraform (SW). Monitoring: CSBAudior (SW) [K. A. Torkura, M. I. H. Sukmana, T. Strauss, H. Graupner, F. Cheng,and C. Meinel, ``CSBAuditor: Proactive security risk analysis for cloudstorage broker systems,'' in Proc. IEEE 17th Int. Symp. Netw. Comput.Appl. (NCA), Nov. 2018, pp. 1â€‚10.], Log4J (SW), Cloud logging mechanisms: AWSCloudWatch (SW) and GCP StackDriver (SW).  Hardware: Cloudstrike is deployed using Intel(R) Core (TM) i5-5200U CPU, 2.20Ghz processor, 8GBRAM and 1 TB HDD. | Cloudstrike is evaluated against a cloud infrastructure test-bed that depicts an enterprise cloud environment, comprised of assets deployed on Amazon Web Services (AWS) and Goolge Cloud Platfrom (GCP). They adopted the cloud testing methodology proposed by the CSA's Cloud Penetration Testing Play book. The experiments  are focused on IAM (users, policies) and cloud storage service (S3 buckets, configurations). Fifty user accounts are provisioned on AWS and GCP cloud infrastructure, 25 users per cloud. Each user account is properly configured using privilege separation concepts. The evaluation targeted two aspects: (1) Time Perfromance: this experiment aims at evaluating the performance of CloudStrike w.r.t time overhead while injecting security faults (workloads), (2) recovery operations: CloudStrike performs recovery operations on completion of security fault injection campaigns. So this experimet aims to evaluate the impact of these operations to gain insights of the overhead of recovery, (3) CPU and memory consumptions, and (4) security evaluation: to evalaute Cloudstrike from a security perspective i.e., whehter CloudStrike proves security hypotheses and provide guidance on appropriate security countermeasures. Cloudstrike is deployed using Intel(R) Core (TM) i5-5200U CPU, 2.20Ghz processor, 8GBRAM and 1 TB HDD. |                                                                                                                                                                                                   Quantitative: time to complete an attack. Qualitative: API calls for recovery operations. Quantitative: CPU and Memory. Qualitative: Security performance. _x000D_                                                                                                                                                                                                   | Time to complete attacks on GCP: low attack rate (30%) takes around 190 Seconds, medium attack rate (60%) takes 290 Seconds, and high attack rate (90%) takes 360 Seconds. Considering AWS: Low takes 38 seconds, medium takes 58 Seconds, and high takes 75 seconds. Recovery operations: these operations requires more API calls than those required by fault injection since this operation executes global checks for all assets using the state transition analysis technique and expected-state. CPU consumption is less than 10 %. The GCP API has a higher overhead due to reauthentication and more complex HTTP requests/responses, hence more CPU is utilized. Memory consumptions ranges from 28MB to 175MB max corresponding to the rise of attack rates. Regarding the effect of Cloudstrike on security, out of 10 executed attacks, only one detection captured the hypotheses tested via the fault injection campaigns.  Specifically, the only hypothesis proven right was Alarms will be triggered if S3 bucket policies are altered. Accordingly, the cloud infrastructure is successfully compromised by Cloudstrike._x000D_ |                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    Consequences: based on the fault injections conducted for evaluation, the resulted knowledge can be exploited as a guide to implement more effective detection rules on the AWS platfrom. SCE provides a test-based approach that  provides clearer guidance on which security efforts to focus and what configurations are not secure. The  use of attack graphs would aid automation and integration with other tools._x000D_                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     |          nan           |
